      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sparks From a Debate, in New York and Beyond</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peter Philip letter says issue in New York Senate campaign is not whether Repr Rick Laziosupported Newt Gingrich as Republican leader, but whether he still stands by votes such as one to eliminate Education Department</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>Hillary Rodham Clinton made much of Representative Rick A. Lazio's association with Newt Gingrich. But the issue is not whether Mr. Lazio supported Mr. Gingrich. Of course he did. Mr. Gingrich was his party's leader in the House. The issue is whether Mr. Lazio still stands by, for example, his vote to eliminate the Department of Education or his support for a balanced-budget amendment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>Hillary Rodham Clinton made much of Representative Rick A. Lazio's association with Newt Gingrich. But the issue is not whether Mr. Lazio supported Mr. Gingrich. Of course he did. Mr. Gingrich was his party's leader in the House. The issue is whether Mr. Lazio still stands by, for example, his vote to eliminate the Department of Education or his support for a balanced-budget amendment.</p>
        <p>There is nothing wrong with politicians' acknowledging that they have sometimes made mistakes. The public would have more respect for them if they did.</p>
        <p>PETER PHILIP  Hillsdale, N.J., Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
